ment often has considerable impacts on the well-being of populations in the Global South. At the same time, multinational corporations today cannot completely distance or isolate themselves from the political, economic, and social contexts they are interacting in and with. Drawing on theoretical debates about the links between resource extraction and socio-economic development, multi-scalar negotiations of ethics in mining governance are ethnographically retraced. In terms of gains and benefits, these negotiations manifest themselves spatially, providing access for some actors while excluding others.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aGold mines and miningxMoral and ethical aspectszBurkina Faso. 0aGold mines and miningxSocial aspectszBurkina Faso. 4aGoldanbau. 4aRohstoffgewinnung. 4aglobaler Bergbaukapitalismus. 4asozioökonomische Entwicklung. 7aHISTORY / Modern / General.2bisacsh  aExtraction of raw materials.  aGlobal mining capitalism.  aGold cultivation.  aSocio-economic development.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishz978311075408708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021z9783110753851oZDB-23-DEG0 cEPUBz97831106902310 cprintz978311068996940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311069016340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110690163423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110690163/original  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075408-7  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishb2021  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE